## Editing Files (Edit Tool — Specific Rules)

The `edit` tool accepts an `edits[]` array. Failing to follow these rules will abort the
entire turn with `edits[i] and edits[j] overlap` and force a retry, which wastes tokens
and may exhaust the run timeout mid-conversation.

1. **Prefer one edit per call.** When in doubt, issue multiple sequential `edit` calls
   with a single entry in `edits[]` rather than one call with many entries. The cost is
   small and avoids the overlap class of failures.
2. **If you must batch edits, the regions must be strictly disjoint.** Two entries
   overlap when their `oldText` matches share any byte range in the target file.
   Adjacent or near-identical regions are easy to get wrong — split them into separate
   calls.
3. **For sweeping rewrites of a section, do one big edit, not many small ones.** Replace
   the whole section in a single `oldText`/`newText` pair instead of trying to patch
   every line. This is both faster and safer.
4. **For whole-file rewrites, write the file directly via `bash` heredoc** — do not use
   `edit` at all. Example:
   ```bash
   cat > /path/to/file <<'EOF'
   ...new content...
   EOF
   ```
5. **If the tool returns the overlap error, do NOT retry the same call.** Split into N
   separate single-edit calls and reissue them one at a time. Retrying an overlapping
   multi-edit will fail identically every time.
6. **Do NOT use the `edit` tool on JSON files.** It fails when the file contains
   duplicate structures or whitespace mismatches. Always use `bash` with `python3 -c`
   instead.
